Species.Comments: This bird was soaring  and would swoop over the riparian zone in the wind. He was all white below, longer wings,with black on the wingtips and only light streaking on wings. Checklist.Comments: Weather clear and cool; temp low 50s.  Cooperative effort to capture/band Yellow Rails for Kelly Morris's graduate research project focusing on the winter ecology of this species.  Rails were flushed using weighted ropes dragged over high marsh and captured by hand using fish nets at dark.  Other species incidentally flushed/captured were also identified and counted when id was possible.  Lithobates sphenocephala heard calling from adjacent flat pine woods.

Other species incidentally flushed were also identified and counted when id was possible.

Species.Comments: From the group shelter go towards the water. He was across the lake westward at the adjacent shore (along hancock trail). I heard him first. Unmistakable cree-aw with a downward slur. I then saw him on a snag. Yellow underneath, and could make out a brown body, White throat and Dark cap. Checklist.Comments: Weather clear and cool; temp low 50s.  Cooperative effort to capture/band Yellow Rails for Kelly Morris's graduate research project focusing on the winter ecology of this species.  Rails were flushed using weighted ropes dragged over high marsh and captured by hand using fish nets at dark.  Other species incidentally flushed/captured were also identified and counted when id was possible.  Lithobates sphenocephala heard calling from adjacent flat pine woods.

Common.Name: Swamp Sparrow
Scientific.Name: Melospiza georgiana
Checklist.Comments: Weather foggy with periods of drizzle/showers and mild; temp 68 F.  Cooperative effort to capture/band Yellow Rails for Kelly Morris's graduate research project focusing on the winter ecology of this species.  Yellow Rails were flushed using weighted ropes dragged over savanna and captured by hand using fish nets after civil twilight.  Other species incidentally flushed were also identified and counted when id was possible.

Species.Comments: Numerous sparrows flushed during rope drags.  Likely Swamp/Song sparrows.
Checklist.Comments: Weather foggy with periods of drizzle/showers and mild; temp 68 F.  Cooperative effort to capture/band Yellow Rails for Kelly Morris's graduate research project focusing on the winter ecology of this species.  Yellow Rails were flushed using weighted ropes dragged over savanna and captured by hand using fish nets after civil twilight.  Other species incidentally flushed were also identified and counted when id was possible.
